e","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":2,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Trevett was born in 1380, in Orchard Portman, Somerset, England, her father, Thomas Trevett III, was 25 and her mother, Elizabeth de Limbury, was 23. She married William Orchard in 1399, in Orchard Portman, Somerset, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1440, in her hometown, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1380–1440":"1380–1440","1370–Male":"1370–Surnud","1380–1419":"1380–1419","1380–1472":"1380–1472","1407–1472":"1407–1472","1412–1420":"1412–1420","1404–1472":"1404–1472","1355–1410":"1355–1410","1358–1409":"1358–1409","21 June 1420":"21. juuni 1420","1440":"1440","1472":"1472","1382":"1382","1370":"1